      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. that's a good start. could you add a little more warmth to the closing? like, we really want them to stay in our talent pool for next year. also, can you provide a slightly shorter version for a LinkedIn message or something more casual? something less formal than the email.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "For warmth and keeping the door open, you need to make the closing sound less like a final \"no\" and more like a \"maybe later, if you're willing to share your best work with us.\" It's like offering a slightly stale, but still edible, piece of bread to a very hungry, highly skilled wolf.\n\nHere is the revised, warmer email closing, followed by the shorter LinkedIn version.\n\n***\n\n### **Revised Warm Email Closing**\n\n(Insert this after the sentence: \"Please know this decision was not a reflection of your talent—you are a very strong engineer, and we truly enjoyed getting to know you.\")\n\n\"We were particularly impressed by [mention a specific positive, e.g., your architectural thinking on X project], and we sincerely hope this isn't the end of our connection. We would love to keep your profile active in our talent pool for future roles that might align even more closely with your strengths. Please feel free to connect with me on LinkedIn, and we wish you the absolute best in your search!\"\n\n***\n\n### **Casual LinkedIn Message Version**\n\n(This is much shorter, designed for a quick, friendly tap on the shoulder.)\n\n\"Hi [Candidate Name",
